{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bf6edb2c-b7d1-4d14-9fd3-0138f8ca7f3c","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect a trace:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                         # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert for **Speedscope** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n# then open at https://speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` env var with `dotnet-dsrouter` from outside the pod.\n- For production, prefer `--duration 30` (seconds) to avoid oversized traces.\n- `--profile cpu-sampling` is lightweight (~5% overhead) and safe for production use.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae78a71a-bb2e-4aed-8856-094b4fc4ed6b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":420,"requestId":"410F:B1B22:7846E26:83F6A42:69F15EBA"},"id":"a87c86fe-8c2c-48c4-88db-b48adc16626f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:28:35.840Z","parentId":"818d1876-917c-4ab3-8efd-15a5fa1db6fb"}
